These last five days have been rough. Nothing, and I mean nothing can prepare you for the loss of your sister. On Thursday, my sister Heather went home to Jesus.

Although I know for a fact, I’ll see her again up in Heaven, my heart aches for her here on Earth.

It’s going to be a long wait before I can hear your laugh, feel those hugs where it felt like we could crush each other, or even exchange those looks that us three siblings just UNDERSTOOD. Until then, I’ll miss you in this life, I’ll miss singing along to our favorite songs with you, doing our makeup together, our sister dates, and simply laughing until our bellies hurt.

This little tail is missing her cool older sister that she always looked up to. ✨

Heather had an unshakable faith in God, was an extremely positive person, absolutely fearless, and just knew things would work out. In her 32 years, that she was on this earth, there was so much she taught us and left us with. 

I love you so much Heather, we all love and miss you. 💗 We’ll see you again. 💗 

Lorelei lost a mother. My mom and dad lost a daughter; my brother and I lost a sister, and my heart breaks for everyone who knew her light. Please keep our family in your prayers during this time 🕊️🤍
———
Edit: Thank you for all your support, love, donations, and for offering condolences and prayers for our family. 💕💐💕

We celebrated your life on Friday and both our maternal and paternal sides of the family came together in love for you, even the animals gathered gracefully as we laid your earthly body to rest. Heather, Bang, my sisteroonie, sister bear, we are going to miss you immensely in this life until we can be together again in heaven. 💖

If there’s one thing we know for sure, you wouldn’t have wanted us to cry, you’re living it up with Jesus right now and dancing on those streets of gold. Instead of crying, you would say for us to honor your memory by living our lives to the fullest, being forgiving, and most importantly, loving heartily just like you did. 🫶🏽

Coming here to express gratitude to each and every person who showed up in any way possible, whether it was in the form of bringing food, donations, in words, or by being physically there for our family. To the family who helped coordinate everything, we are so so so thankful. The love everyone showed us meant the whole world to us. Ahéhee nitsaago 🤲🏽💗

🔴Today, May 5 is National Day of Awareness for Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women. 🔴

A few facts to think over…

-Indigenous Women face murder rates that are more than 10x the national average. (The U.S. Department of Justice)

-More than 4 out of 5 (83.5%) Indigenous women have experienced violence in their lifetime. (National Institute of Justice)

-65% of Indigenous Transgender people have experienced sexual assault at some point in their life. (www.transequality.org)

It’s important to remember that these numbers only reflect those who have come forward and reported these acts of violence. The numbers are much higher.

Indigenous Peoples grieve over this reality that our women, girls, trans, Two-Spirits, and relatives live in today, however we remain hopeful. We pray for families affected by this and pray that through the great organizations and people who are fighting for our relatives, that one day, this will stop.

So many of us in Indigenous communities know someone who is missing and, even tragically, we know someone who has been murdered. We must bring awareness and be the voice for those who cannot be heard. This must end.

#MMIWGActionNow #NoMoreStolenSisters #MMIWG #MMIW #MMIWGT2S

On Tuesday, I got a chance to swing by the Chelsea piers and look at some geese who photobombed me, menacingly. Luckily didn’t ruffle any feathers 🤭 and got to my meetings in one piece! Then after work, got to shoot some hoops, or at least— see some hoops being shot 😅 (fourth slide)

Then we met up with my family to eat at Restoration Hardware’s Rooftop Restaurant in the Meat Packing district (slides 2 & 3) where I had the chicken (forgot to get a photo) and it was delicious! Y’all know how I feel about chicken 😍 but I was feelin’ food shy so I couldn’t finish it :/

Then we headed on over to the east village to play some billiards. Team Small & Tall (@huddleberryfinn and I) had a true redemption arc by winning the last game, with me shooting the winning shot! Sorry Gemini Gang (@t_glasses & @phillip.bread) 🤷🏽‍♀️

Before the night was fully over, we headed to Joe’s Pizza and got some midnight slices.

Wednesday was mostly business, business, business in the morning so I didn’t snap any photos really. Our evening ended with a reservation at The Polo Bar ✨

I had the special of the night which was the Manhattan Burger. It had smoked Gouda, bacon, and pickled jalapeños. Y’all it was so so so good 😮‍💨

Be back later with more on the nyc trip 🤗

NYC day 5 and day 6 ✨🌆✨

Thursday was my final full day in the city and I made the most out of my free time by going to the weaving exhibit: Shaped By The Loom at the Bard Graduate Center Gallery in the Upper West Side. From there I ventured out of Manhattan and finally gave Brooklyn a proper visit 😇 went to this place called Bar Blondeau and realized afterwards, we basically had an elevated hot dog, chicken strips (they called it fried chicken tho 👀) and fries. The best though 🫶🏽 We also had their oysters and then cheesecake for dessert (not pictured 😵‍💫) it was a great way to end the trip ✨

Friday morning was Business Bear Vibes in the morning, was a travel day, and then we arrived back in the southwest later that night. We met up with our cousin @hastiin_tsin . Ended the night at a Mexican restaurant where I had possibly the best birria I’ve had??? We also happened to come in on a night when karaoke was going on (not pictured) and had us awwwlll in our feelings! 🤧

That wraps up our trip, until next time nyc 🌃 see ya soon ✨

Happy birthday daddy-o! 🥳💕

Dad, I want to thank you so much for all of your guidance, wisdom, and most importantly, your love. Super super super grateful for the work ethic you’ve instilled in me since I was a kid. Absolutely excited to see what 54 has in store, definitely lots more travel! I love you x 1,000,000,000,000 🥳🫶🏽🎉

In my experience, skateboarding has always been fun. However when I step back, I understand it’s also a great meditative space for me to clear my head and a place to sort out my creative ideas. Incredibly grateful for the ways that skating has remained good to me throughout my life. 🥰

Grateful to @Nike N7 and @hibbettsports for tagging along with me to my local-ish skatepark, even if it was a bit of a drive 😅

I often get asked how I decided to skate sandstone. It honestly started when I was looking for grandma’s lost goats one day, out on the land. In the middle of the grasslands, there was a huge sandstone outcropping and my brother asked, “do you think you could skate that?” To which I grabbed my skateboard, which was luckily in the truck, and tried it. ✨

Now, it’s become one of my favorite spots to skate. I have to thank the love and special connection that so many of us Diné have to the land, for the happy accident that became my experience with sandstone skating. ✨🛹✨

Thank you @Nike N7 & @hibbettsports for following me to my favorite sandstone spots 🫶🏽

We have the power to create how our days will go. Choosing to be positive, focusing on the good, finding beauty in everything, and spreading joy is something I try to do everyday. For me, that’s how I show what it’s like to walk in beauty ✨💖✨

Thank you @Nike N7 and @hibbettsports for allowing me to share a bit of my story with the world. 🌎💗

June was exciting. A lot of things happened behind the scenes and I got to enjoy time here at home. 🥰

Most exciting part was definitely being able to share the Nike N7 / Hibbett campaign with y’all and being able to help in donating some funds to my local-ish skatepark (separate post coming!)

Most random part of June was unexpectedly getting invested in the happenings of the Men’s College Baseball World Series and rooting for the LSU Tigers. The baseball bug bit me BAD, bc I even had a superstition about keeping a stuffed tiger (Luci) under my left arm for the duration of the games so they would win 😅

Grateful for June and excited for July. Also, we’re getting so much closer to Santa Fe Ndn Market in August !! ✨ see y’all here around the same time in about a month for another recap? 😌

Thankful to present this check to Kayenta Township for the Kayenta Skate Park on Hibbett and Nike’s behalf. 💖

Back in May, I got to work on a campaign with @HibbettSports and @Nike N7 for the Dunk Low Decon SB and when the project shoot was complete they advised me that they wanted me to choose a skatepark to donate to. Right away, I knew the skatepark I wanted to donate to, that has had such a huge impact on me is: the Kayenta Skatepark.

Then on Go Skate Day (June 21) I was able to present a $25,000 check to Kayenta Skatepark via Kayenta Township on Hibbett and Nike’s behalf. I was able to say a few words of appreciation for the skatepark. 🩷

To say I’m grateful for this partnership is an understatement. I’m extremely stoked to see this amount be put towards the skate park I grew up with. This is where I learned how to drop in, learned how to ride ramps in general, and so many other skating firsts happened here! So grateful that this partnership allowed me to give back to the skate community I became a part of in my middle school & high school years. Axhéhee (Thank you) Hibbett and Nike ✨💖✨

✨ July is Cleft and Craniofacial Awareness month ✨ 

Being born with a bilateral cleft lip and palate has had it’s challenges, however I’m so grateful to everyone from my family, to my doctors, and my friends who have been there for me throughout my journey. 💖 whether you’re someone who has been incredibly kind or not-so-kind, I’m glad that you were able to tech me something in this life so far about kindness and compassion.

To all my fellow clefties, I love y’all so much and you all continually inspire me. ✨💖✨

When I’m weaving, I go back to my inner-child and how fascinated Lil Omi was with weaving. It seemed so magical seeing my grandma create entire masterpieces with her loom and wool. Back then, my creativity was focused on drawing and always had wanted to learn how to weave. Now that I’m older and have learned how to weave, I get the same amount of creative joy and return to that inner-child when I’m at the loom. ✨

I hope Lil Omi is just as stoked I am that we learned how to weave and create magic just like our grandmas before 💖

✨ #YourInnerChildIsAnArtist #H2YSummerArtCamp @herestoyou_h2y ✨

When I checked the mail on Monday, I got some exciting news! The official welcome letter from Phoenix Children’s Center for Cleft and Craniofacial Care’s Advisory Board came in to welcome me as their newest board member!

With all of the amazing things going on in my life, I now get to advocate for cleft and Craniofacial care for our Indigenous and Rural communities. 💗 This is such a blessing to be the first Native American on their board and I’m humbled to share my perspective.

Constantly seeing the juxtaposition of how easily accessible the care is for people in the city and the hurdles we had to jump once we moved back to Navajo Nation when I was 12 urged me to discuss it with my Craniofacial doctors, Dr. Stephen Beals and Dr. Patricia Beals. 

In April, Phoenix Children’s offered me a board position.

My hope is to bring visibility to the people I’ve met so far in my life that mention that they wish that they had gotten the full amount of Cleft and Craniofacial care that we all deserve to live a normal life. All we want is normalcy and I want to make sure that we can have the same access to medical care as others. Axhéhee Phoenix Children’s Cleft and Craniofacial Center for bringing me on. ✨
———
Also, my brother asked if our first board meeting will be in Vegas in December (*ahem* if you know, you know 😂 *ahem*) but I was like, “nooo, our first meeting is later in September in Phoenix” 😅

Meet the first #RLArtistInResidence, @NaiomiGlasses. 

Naiomi is a seventh-generation Diné (Navajo) textile artist and designer whose love for the Navajo way of life is at the center of everything she creates. 

To learn more about Naiomi, watch the short film and explore the #PoloRalphLauren x #NaiomiGlasses collection via the link in bio.

The #RLArtistInResidence program is one of the ways #RalphLauren is building a model of collaboration with the artisans that sustain heritage craft.

The #PoloRalphLauren x #NaiomiGlasses collection honors Navajo patternwork and centuries-old weaving traditions. 

“When people wear the collection, I want them to feel empowered. I want them to feel confident, and I want them to know they are supporting the work of a Native artist.” —@NaiomiGlasses  

Learn more about our Artist in Residence program and watch the short film via the link in bio.

Honored to be the inaugural Ralph Lauren Artist in Residence and to present you all the @poloralphlauren x #NaiomiGlasses collection.

When designing this collection, I imagined seeing my family and the people I love wear these pieces out in the world.

To see the collection (that took almost two years) being presented to the world is a dream come true. This collection I designed with #PoloRalphLauren came to life on the very land that inspired my creativity, and sharing this moment alongside my family (mom, dad, brother, cousins, niece) and friends who feel like family, all while being beautifully captured by Ryan Redcorn (Osage @redcorn) and Daryn Sells (Diné - Navajo @darynpaigesells) and for everyone involved, I’m extremely thankful.

I’m grateful this collection celebrates the love of the land, the love I have for my family and friends. Excited to share more, however I just wanted to share how special this campaign is to me 🫶🏽

#RLArtistInResidence

THIS SUNDAY: At 26, Navajo artist @NaiomiGlasses is passing down generations of a rich Native American tradition of weaving through her collaboration with @RalphLauren, by becoming the fashion house’s first artist-in-residence.

What a Friday night! Thank you @cultured_mag and @ralphlauren for co-hosting such a beautiful event to celebrate the @poloralphlauren x #NaiomiGlasses Love of The Land collection at the Ralph Lauren store in Aspen, Colorado.

Truly honored to be the inaugural #RLArtistInResidence and I’m grateful for the many wonderful people who joined us that night, including @nachofigueras with @delfinablaquier and Navajo Nation Vice President Richelle Montoya(@montoyarich3ll3). You all made my second time (ever) in Aspen an unforgettable one! 🥰

+ Behind the Design Process +
When I talk about the design process for the @poloralphlauren x #NaiomiGlasses collection and how fully immersed I was, this is what I mean. Throughout the processes, my voice and artistic vision was heard and each piece that was made reflects exactly how I would make each piece. Among the 32 pieces in this first capsule, you can find certain pieces where I wanted the background color to be a certain blend of colors, and to mimic the colors in a handspun weaving, so the yarn was either handspun in the piece or we blended three different colors or we used natural, undyed wool or other techniques to achieve certain looks. I’m really proud of the wool wrap and The Great Ranch Coat which utilize natural, undyed wool colors, that reflect the same colors just like my brother @t_glasses and I used in our early weavings.

Each detail was taken into consideration, from tags to buttons. Yes, even the buttons!

A big part of my own design inspiration comes from utilitarian Navajo weavings pre-trading posts, such as wearing blankets and rug dresses. Within this collection, I envisioned what a modern day wearing blanket could look like as a wrap or, even a coat.

To be completely honest, I’m not entirely sure if words will ever describe the depth of emotions I feel for this first collection. I poured so much of my heart and soul into each piece. For my Ralph Lauren family, my own family, the incredible Indigenous jewelers I was able to handpick, and to everyone who had any part of this collection, I’m extremely thankful for you. It truly is an honor to be the inaugural #RLArtistInResidence and I’m grateful to share the Love of The Land with each and every one of you in every part of the world. 💗

Happy heavenly birthday to my sister Heather 😇💖

It feels strange not having you here with us. Part of me still thinks that you’re out on one of your many adventures and you’ll call us up to give us all the details on “what’s the haps” is in your world.

You left this world in March of this year and yet, I still don’t feel like you’re entirely gone. Maybe that’s because as a family, we all still talk about you like you’re here with us. You live on in our memories and our many photos we took. (You and I sure loved us our selfies 🤭💗) We live our lives like you would’ve encouraged us to. You were so incredibly fearless, loved wholeheartedly, and were so incredibly kind.

You’ve visited me in a couple of dreams since you’ve gone home to our Heavenly Father. I cherish those dreams more than anything, and I know we’ll all collectively reunite someday. I’m not even sure if earthside birthdays are a big deal in heaven or if everyday is just a celebration? But I hope you’re going a lil harder than usual today 🤭🥳

It’s just that mom, dad, TJ, and I sure miss having you around on Earth. What gives us comfort is knowing how much you loved us and how you loved your daughter Lorelei. We all love you Heather and we miss you. 💗
